statement.p:
If possible, find the indicated values for the rational function. 
If the value does not exist, enter  Does not exist .  
f(x) = \frac{x^{2}+x-3}{x+3}

static.solution:
SOLUTION
(a) f(x)= \frac{9}{3 - (2)^3} = -{\frac{9}{5}}.
(b) We have y = f(x) = 9 = \frac{9}{3 - x^3}, so, solving for x, \begin{aligned} 9(3 - x^3) \amp = 9\\ (3 - x^3) \amp = 1\\ x^3 \amp = 3 - 1 = 2\\ x \amp = 2^{1/3}. \end{aligned}

statement.p:
Express the function y = \sqrt{ x^2 + 9 } 
as a composition y = f(g(x)) of two simpler
functions y = f(u) and u = g(x).

static.solution:
SOLUTION
In order to find the zeros, we set the function equal to zero and solve for r by factoring: \begin{aligned} 2 r^2 + 14 r + 12 \amp = 0\\ 2 \left( r^2 + 7 r + 6 \right) \amp = 0 \\ 2 ( r + 6)(r + 1) \amp = 0 \end{aligned}
Since (r + 6 ) and (r + 1 ) are factors, there are two zeros at r = -6 and r = -1.

